Another week, and another plan to end the slaughter lies in tatters. Syrian warplanes are back in the skies after a brief lull, dropping bombs that President Bashar al-Assad and his Russian backers hope will finally crush rebel forces holed up in the city’s besieged east. The bombs have knocked out all of the east’s hospitals, says the World Health Organisation. As pro-government ground forces try to punch through rebel lines, food, fuel and water for the 250,000 or so besieged residents are running dangerously low. Efforts to stop the killing have failed. Over the weekend, the Syrian government dismissed a UN plan that would have left rebels in control of the east if al-Qaeda-linked jihadists agreed to leave. Mr Assad’s gamble—that Western powers will not intervene more forcefully to stop the bloodshed—is paying off. The UN’s Syria envoy says eastern Aleppo may collapse by Christmas

The key lies in the relatively weak Syrian army. The Russian presence in Syria is almost exclusively contained to a couple of bases and command centres in the Latakia province, and air strikes which originate from said bases. To completely demolish a city from the sky is the easy part - especially when your enemy lacks proper equipment to resist airborne attacks. The difficult part is for the Syrian army to defeat entrenched rebels in guerilla warfare, in the eastern half of the once greatest city in all of Syria. It's not impossible, and it looks like it certainly will happen eventually, but chances are it will be a prolonged battle lasting in to the first half of 2017.

I'm now curious as to whether modern wargamers have yet created any sort of "credibility" value, a kind of capacity function (similar maybe in some ways to the notion of "political capital" on the domestic front). It would be something related to troop morale, but would also encompass public and alliance support, command reliability, future diplomatic success, and some number of other effects. The value would be determined as a function of internally and externally generated propositions, as well as propositions implied from historical facts. I'm thinking about this because the Western alliance, in particular the United States, continues to take severe hits on the credibility front. • "Proxy" war no more. Allegations that the U.S. is now directly attacking Syrian troops (and effectively supporting ISIS in doing so). • Continued allegations that United States is supporting JFS terrorist group, which the U.S. refuses to renounce. • Allegations by Russia that it is the U.S. (only) that is keeping the text of the current ceasefire agreement secret (thus implying that there is some untoward intention contained within the agreement)
